05272nam a22010455i 9780520928565DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021697132  a97805209285657 a10.1525/97805209285652doi  a(DE-B1597)520678  a(OCoLC)52998857  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aAM79.T8 4aAM79.T8bS53 2003 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a069/.09561a956.0151 aShaw, Wendy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPossessors and Possessed :bMuseums, Archaeology, and the Visualization of History in the Late Ottoman Empire /cWendy Shaw. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Orthography -- tIntroduction -- t1. Moving toward the Museum: The Collection of Antique Spolia -- t2. Parallel Collections of Weapons and Antiquities -- t3. The Rise of the Imperial Museum -- t4. The Dialectic of Law and Infringement -- t5. Technologies of Collection: Railroads and Cameras -- t6. Antiquities Collections in the Imperial Museum -- t7. Islamic Arts in Imperial Collections -- t8. Military Collections in the Late Empire -- t9. Islamic and Archaeological Antiquities after the Young Turk Revolution -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPossessors and Possessed analyzes how and why museums—characteristically Western institutions—emerged in the late-nineteenth-century Ottoman Empire. Shaw argues that, rather than directly emulating post-Enlightenment museums of Western Europe, Ottoman elites produced categories of collection and modes of display appropriate to framing a new identity for the empire in the modern era. In contrast to late-nineteenth-century Euro-American museums, which utilized organizational schema based on positivist notions of progress to organize exhibits of fine arts, Ottoman museums featured military spoils and antiquities long before they turned to the "Islamic" collections with which they might have been more readily associated. The development of these various modes of collection reflected shifting moments in Ottoman identity production. Shaw shows how Ottoman museums were able to use collection and exhibition as devices with which to weave counter-colonial narratives of identity for the Ottoman Empire. Impressive for both the scope and the depth of its research, Possessors and Possessed lays the groundwork for future inquiries into the development of museums outside of the Euro-American milieu.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMuseumsxCollection managementzTurkeyxHistory. 0aMuseumszTurkeyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  a1874 antiquities law.  aabdlaziz.  aabdlhamid ii.  aabdlhamid.  aantique weapons.  aantiquities.  aarchaeology.  aartifacts.  acameras.  achurch of the hagia irene.  acollection management.  acollection.  acolonial narratives.  aconquest.  adisplay.  aempire.  ahistory.  aidentity.  aimperial armory.  aimperial museum.  aimperialism.  aislam.  amiddle east.  amilitary storehouse.  amilitary.  amuseum administration.  amuseum exhibits.  amuseums.  anational identity.  aottoman empire.  aottoman museums.  arailroads.  arelics.  aspoils of war.  aspolia.  atechnology.  aturkey.  aturks.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023335540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092856540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978052092856